</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31A6525FFE7EF3263EDFB27FD15FAF6" pageId="8" pageNumber="391" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BBF36AEFFE7EF3263EDFB27FD15FAF6" blockId="8.[175,1005,194,1570]" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis id="B974EABCFFE7EF3263EDFB27FED0FB1D" bold="true" box="[199,314,1250,1272]" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">Etymology.</emphasis>
The epithet 
<taxonomicName id="4C004D2DFFE7EF326297FB27FDE2FB12" authorityName="Liebherr" authorityYear="2009" box="[445,520,1250,1271]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Mecyclothorax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis id="B974EABCFFE7EF326297FB27FDE2FB12" box="[445,520,1250,1271]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
signifies the distinctive yellow legs and tarsi of this species, and is to be treated as a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31A6525FFE7EF3263EDFADCFE09F9C7" pageId="8" pageNumber="391" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BBF36AEFFE7EF3263EDFADCFEE0FA80" blockId="8.[175,1005,194,1570]" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis id="B974EABCFFE7EF3263EDFADCFEACFACA" bold="true" box="[199,326,1305,1327]" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">Distribution.</emphasis>
Recorded from the summit ridge of Lanai at Lanaihale and Waiakeakua (
<figureCitation id="133B2A2BFFE7EF32626BFAF1FE79FAAF" box="[321,403,1332,1354]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="11.[167,198,1309,1328]" captionTargetBox="[172,950,194,1286]" captionTargetId="figure-17@11.[172,950,194,1287]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Fig. 5. Known distributions of carabid beetle species on Lanai. A. Mecyclothorax flavipes. B. M. mundanus. C. M. filipes. D. Bembidion ignicola. E. Blackburnia lanaiensis. F. Bl. lucipetens." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4924366" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4924366/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
), two localities near 
<quantity id="4CF89B4BFFE7EF32615EFAF1FD2CFAAF" box="[628,710,1332,1354]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="391" unit="m" value="1000.0">1,000 m</quantity>
elevation and separated by 
<quantity id="4CF89B4BFFE7EF326385FA8AFEECFA80" box="[175,262,1359,1381]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" pageId="8" pageNumber="391" unit="km" value="1.75">1.75 km</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBF36AEFFE7EF3263EDFAAFFE09F9C7" blockId="8.[175,1005,194,1570]" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis id="B974EABCFFE7EF3263EDFAAFFEF1FA65" bold="true" box="[199,283,1386,1408]" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">Habitat.</emphasis>
Three of the 
<specimenCount id="9D06FD27FFE7EF32629FFAAFFDBBFA65" box="[437,593,1386,1408]" pageId="8" pageNumber="391" type="generic">four specimens</specimenCount>
are recorded from the trunks of nonnative trees, either 
<taxonomicName id="4C004D2DFFE7EF3262A2FA43FE04FA7E" box="[392,494,1414,1435]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Casuarinaceae" genus="Casuarina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="8" pageNumber="391" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B974EABCFFE7EF3262A2FA43FE04FA7E" box="[392,494,1414,1435]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">Casuarina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="4C004D2DFFE7EF32610AFA43FD64FA7E" box="[544,654,1414,1435]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eucalyptus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="8" pageNumber="391" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B974EABCFFE7EF32610AFA43FD64FA7E" box="[544,654,1414,1435]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">Eucalyptus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, within the native cloud forest community (
<figureCitation id="133B2A2BFFE7EF326218FA65FE85FA53" box="[306,367,1440,1462]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[167,198,915,934]" captionTargetBox="[181,941,194,893]" captionTargetId="figure-200@3.[181,941,194,893]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Pre-Polynesian vegetation communities on the island of Lanai (after Hobdy 1993): 1) cloud forest; 2) mesic forest; 3) dry forest; 4) arid grassland and shrubland; 5) coast and strand." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4924358" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4924358/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Thus it appears this species includes arboreal microhabitats within its ecological preferences, though whether that substrate comprises native or non-native plant species is of lesser importance. The 1993 specimen was collected during a nighttime stop, along with 
<taxonomicName id="4C004D2DFFE7EF3261BDFA37FC2DF9E2" authority="(Sharp)" baseAuthorityName="Sharp" baseAuthorityYear="1903" box="[663,967,1521,1543]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Blackburnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="depressa">
<emphasis id="B974EABCFFE7EF3261BDFA37FC84F9E2" box="[663,878,1522,1543]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">Blackburnia depressa</emphasis>
(Sharp)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C004D2DFFE7EF3260FCFA37FEABF9C7" authority="(Sharp)" baseAuthorityName="Sharp" baseAuthorityYear="1903" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Mecyclothorax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="filipes">
<emphasis id="B974EABCFFE7EF3260FCFA37FF00F9C7" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">B. filipes</emphasis>
(Sharp)
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C004D2DFFE7EF326256F9C8FE37F9C7" baseAuthorityName="Sharp" baseAuthorityYear="1903" box="[380,477,1549,1570]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Mecyclothorax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="filipes">
<emphasis id="B974EABCFFE7EF326256F9C8FE37F9C7" box="[380,477,1549,1570]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="391">M. filipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
